        "body": "Welcome to the Windows XP simulator. This classic desktop environment runs entirely in your browser.\n\nYou can explore the file system, browse the web, run applications, and use familiar Windows XP controls."
      },
      "gettingStarted": {
        "title": "Getting Started",
        "body": "Try these common tasks:\n\n1. Double-click a desktop icon to open it\n2. Use the Start menu to find programs\n3. Drag a title bar to move a window\n4. Resize supported windows\n5. Use the taskbar to manage open windows"
      },
      "desktop": {
        "title": "Desktop Introduction",
        "body": "The Windows XP desktop contains:\n\n- Icons for programs, folders, and files\n- A taskbar for open windows and notification icons\n- The Start menu for programs and system features\n- A configurable desktop background"
      },
      "explorer": {
        "title": "File Explorer",
        "body": "File Explorer manages files and folders.\n\nYou can browse folders, create and rename items, move files to the Recycle Bin, and view properties."
      },
      "internet": {
        "title": "Internet Explorer",
        "body": "Internet Explorer is the built-in web browser.\n\nUse the address bar, navigation buttons, browsing history, favorites, and the Home button to browse available pages."
      },
      "applications": {
        "title": "Applications",
        "body": "The English desktop includes classic system tools such as Notepad, Paint, Calculator, Windows Media Player, Minesweeper, Solitaire, Internet Explorer, and File Explorer."
      },
      "settings": {
        "title": "System Settings",
        "body": "Open Control Panel from the Start menu to change display, sound, mouse, and system settings. Language changes are applied after Windows restarts."
      }
    }
